******
[2]
Date: Wed 11 Sep 2013
Source: New Region [in Russian, trans. Sabine Zentis, edited]
http://www.nr2.ru/asia/459521.html


Kyrgyzstan's Health Ministry has confirmed the facts of human infection with anthrax in the north of the country.

In early September 2013, 2 male villagers with identical symptoms of the disease were taken to the regional hospital in Talas. According to the results of laboratory tests, for one of the residents from the Buckeye-Ata district, the initial diagnosis was confirmed. Analysis of a 33-year-old man showed that he was infected with anthrax. Later, the diagnosis of the 2nd patient also showed a positive result.

Quarantine has been imposed on the village Yntymak in the Talas region in the north of Kyrgyzstan and will last until 21 Sep 2013; if necessary, its duration will be increased.

Meanwhile, another 16 villagers have been hospitalized with similar symptoms; in 2 of them, anthrax infection was also confirmed. Currently, all diseased cases are isolated, and the others are under close medical supervision. According to the Kyrgyz medics, supplies for anthrax treatment have arrived in the region, and so all patients are receiving treatment.

Just before these cases of anthrax in the north of the country, the head physician of the Center Tokmok Gossanepidnadzora, Dr. Raimbek Nurgaziev, warned of a possible epidemic of anthrax in the city. The main reasons for this un-reassuring prognosis were the lack of chlorination facilities at the wells supplying the city with water.

"Water quality is very poor," said Raimbek Nurgaziev. "Water samples showed deviations from the norm and with excessive levels of bacteria. The authorities plan to install water sterilisation, but when will that be? Even today, the levels of enteric diseases among residents are too high, as are cases of hepatitis. In preparing kebabs, they use water from their wells, hence the danger of the epidemic."

Meanwhile, to date, out of 1238 foci of anthrax in Kyrgyzstan, more than half are in a reasonable state [presumably undisturbed - Mod.MHJ].

